<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="143" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="143">Comment.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="143">
New record for Iraq. Previously, this species was only provisionally recorded from Iran based on a single female specimen (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.777.26745" author="Zamani, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" pagination="17 - 41" refId="B31" refString="Zamani, A, Seiedy, M, Saboori, A, Marusik, YM, 2018. The spider genus Pterotricha in Iran, with the description of a new genus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae). ZooKeys 777: 17 - 41, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.777.26745" title="The spider genus Pterotricha in Iran, with the description of a new genus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.777.26745" volume="777" year="2018">Zamani et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
), and specimens of both sexes from United Arab Emirates were only tentatively matched (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/evolsyst.2.2998" author="Zamani, A" journalOrPublisher="Evolutionary Systematics" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" pagination="151 - 161" refId="B28" refString="Zamani, A, 2018. The spider genus Pterotricha Kulczynski, 1903 (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) in the United Arab Emirates. Evolutionary Systematics 2: 151 - 161, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/evolsyst.2.2998" title="The spider genus Pterotricha Kulczynski, 1903 (Araneae, Gnaphosidae) in the United Arab Emirates." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/evolsyst.2.2998" volume="2" year="2018">Zamani 2018</bibRefCitation>
); the finding of the two sexes in the same locality reinforces the correct matching of this female with the male of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. dalmasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="dalmasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. dalmasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="143">
The females of this species were described for the first time by Levy (1995), who provided figures of two 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“forms”">&quot;forms&quot;</normalizedToken>
of the epigyne (Levy 1995: figs 74-75). In our opinion and based on material from Iraq, Iran and UAE, only the form illustrated on fig. 75 is correctly matched with the male of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. dalmasi" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="dalmasi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. dalmasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the one illustrated on fig. 74 belongs to another (perhaps undescribed) species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
